text:
I just think it’s really interesting that once I became more visibly Jewish- wearing a tichel or kippah on a daily basis, wearing my hamsa, learning Yiddish- I was immediately faced with (misdirected) transmisogyny- being called transmisogynistic specific slurs, being followed and harrassed off buses, being followed and watched in women’s bathrooms, etc.
It goes to show that transmisogynists and terfs base their ideas on what womanhood is on a white, European, racist, antisemetic, patriarchal caricature of womanhood, and not actual womanhood, which is intrisic to each women, normal or cis., Hey people w morals! Could you reblog this so I have non terfs in the notes and spread awareness? Thank you kindly!

text:
idk what shit-eating truscum needs to hear this, but your rhetoric directly harms people with culturally-specific genders. i’m native and two-spirit, that label describes my gender and my attraction. i use they/them pronouns and your “nonbinaries and cringey stargender trenders aren’t valid” bullshit is getting old. our languages were demonized and erased, our gender and attraction labels along with them. my experiences with dysphoria exist because of colonialist ideas of gender. we have been forced into arbitrary ‘male’ and ‘female’ categories by colonizers for centuries and truscum rhetoric perpetuates racist colonialist violence against natives.
your experiences are not universal, you’re not forwarding justice for trans people, and you’re definitely not an ally to natives or other people of color. you’re just a fucking colonizer. , non-natives, reblog this post

text:
Trauma
If your asexual identity formed because of past trauma, you are still valid. You don’t have to defend yourself, you don’t have to mention it to people who ask why you’re asexual, you don’t need to think “im not really ace”. No matter your reason for your asexuality, it is wonderful and valid. And if, in the future, you decide you aren’t asexual after all, that’s cool too. You weren’t “lying”, you aren’t a “traitor”. text:
An analogy for why you need dysphoria to be trans
For this analogy, we’re going to use depression. Depression is a mental illness which can be treated with antidepressents. For a depressed person, antidepressents can be extremely helpful. There may be a few negative side effects, but the benefit is worth the cost. The meds help this person.
Now, let’s say someone who isn’t depressed desides to take antidepressents. They start taking the antidepressents and, because they weren’t depressed, they don’t help them. There are no positive effects for this person, only negative ones. The meds hurt the person instead of helping them because they never needed them in the first place.
For gender dysphoria, it’s the SAME THING.

We now have a person who has gender dysphoria. Gender dysphoria is a mental illness that can be treated with physical transition, such as HRT and/or sex reassignment surgery. The dysphoric person goes on HRT and find themself much happier and much less dysphoric. The effects of the HRT help them.
On the other hand, we have someone who doesn’t have gender dysphoria. This person, for one reason or another, decides to undergo HRT. However, because they were never dysphoric, the HRT doesn’t help them. The effects of the HRT, for this person, are all unwanted and often actually make the person dysphoric. The effects of HRT don’t help them because they never needed it in the first place.
Don’t undergo medical transition if you aren’t dysphoric. You will NOT like the effects., hey dumbass
im not diagnosed with depression and my doctor doesn’t even suspect i have depression
but i was prescribed antidepressants
and they’ve had a positive effect on my mental health
your analogy fuckin SUCKS, Why would a doctor EVER prescribe something that isn’t medically necessary? The answer: they wouldn’t. Medication can drastically change the way your body functions. Antidepressants, for example, reduce the volume of your hippocampus and your anterior cingulate cortex. They literally CHANGE YOUR BRAIN STRUCTURE. A doctor would never prescribe antidepressants unless necessary because the changes can be very unwanted and possibly lifelong. It’s the same way with dysphoria. There’s a reason you won’t be prescribed hormones unless you’re dysphoric.
So, you’re probably lying. If not, I’d switch doctors., they are medically necessary. the point is you can go on antidepressants without depression because they treat anxiety disorders too, therefore your analogy is bullshit. weird how you’ve researched the precise ways antidepressants affect the brain structure and never once heard that antidepressants aren’t just for depression., Hey, @tired-truescum? My doctor put me on Sertraline to treat my GAD, even though it’s considered an anti-depressant. Most anti depressants, in fact, are used for treating other problems such as neuropathic pain, IBS, sleeping problems, and even migraines. I think medical professionals know what’s best for their patients than some Tumblr user. Please inform yourself on subjects you don’t understand before spouting bullshit, thank you. , The point I’m trying to make is that you shouldn’t take antidepressants unless it’ll medically benefit you in some way. I said depression because, well, that’s usually what antidepressants are used for. If you have no medical condition that can be treated by antidepressants, you shouldn’t take antidepressants because it’ll negatively affect you.
Similarly, if you have no medical condition that can be treated by HRT, you shouldn’t go on HRT because it’ll affect you negatively (reverse dysphoria, unwanted lifelong changes, etc). The only medical condition I can think of that is treated by HRT is gender dysphoria (or perhaps growth problems, but that’s not what tucutes or myself are focused on).

text:
Honestly, one of the funniest and also most frustrating things for me is when someone goes, “I don’t need dysphoria to be trans, and here’s how I know,” and then every single thing they list off is a symptom of dysphoria.
For some reason people have been portraying sex/gender dysphoria as hating one’s own body. This is not the case, and it needs to be corrected. An outlook like this causes a lot of confusion, from overlooking actual dysphoria to misdiagnosing body dysmorphia. Dysphoria is not hating your body.

text:
Stop making people feel bad for detransitioning. It shouldn’t become a common thing, but sometimes people make mistakes. A lot of people who detransition genuinely thought what they are experiencing was dysphoria. And to find out it was actually trauma, or dysmorphia, or whatever else can be very damaging to ones mental health.
Imagine believing for years you are trans. You take hormones, go through surgeries, come out to your loved ones, and possibly lose some. And then you begin to feel worse? Get actual dysphoria? Awful. Having to listen to family members talk about how they KNEW it was just a phase? Awful.
Being mad at detransitioners isn’t going to help them. But giving them support just might.

text:
Poppin’ Party: What’s your favorite thing to do with friends?
   ★ Kasumi Toyama: Do you consider yourself outgoing?
   ★ Arisa Ichigaya: Do you find it easy to make friends?
   ★ Rimi Ushigome: What’s your favorite food?
   ★ Saya Yamabuki: How many siblings do you have?
   ★ Tae Hanazono: What’s your ideal pet?
Afterglow: Are your childhood friends still with you today?
   ◈ Ran Mitake: Do your parents set up expectations for you?
   ◈ Moca Aoba: How long do you sleep each night?
   ◈ Tsugimi Hazawa: Have you ever been in a student council?
   ◈ Himari Uehara: Are you the mom friend of your group?
   ◈ Tomoe Udagawa: Are you more feminine or masculine?
Pastel*Palettes: What’s your aesthetic?
   ✺ Aya Murayama: Are you the leader of the group?
   ✺ Chisato Shirasagi: What’s one thing you’ve did as a child?
   ✺ Eve Wakamiya: Which topic do you find the most fascinating?
   ✺ Hina Hikawa: What’re your trademarks?
   ✺ Maya Yamato: Do you wear glasses?
Roselia: Are you popular?
   ✿ Yukina Minato: What’s your guilty pleasure?
   ✿ Lisa Imai: Are you good at giving advice?
   ✿ Sayo Hikawa: Do you like your siblings (if you have any)?
   ✿ Ako Udagawa: Do you play video games?
   ✿ Rinko Shirokane: What’s a hidden talent of yours?
Hello Happy World: Do you like making others smile?
   ❃ Kokoro Tsurumaki: Do you believe anything is possible?
   ❃ Kanon Matsubara: Do you have a good sense of direction?
   ❃ Karou Seta: Are you dramatic?

   ❃ Misaki Okusawa: Are you an optimist or a pessimist?
   ❃ Michelle: What’s your favorite animal?

text:
do cis people realise that trans people get misgendered even if we pass? a trans man could walk up in a full beard and still be called “miss” because people are transphobic, not because he looks like woman. obviously non-passing trans people get misgendered more often, but there’s really more layers (aka transphobia) to being misgendered apart from “i pass all the time thus no one ever misgenders me”, relatives might misgender you through your entire life, people who know you’re trans might misgender you solely because you are trans, people will misgender you to spite you and they’ll misgender you to harm you (either emotionally, or by outing you). doctors will misgender you if they realise you’re not cis, which can have fatal outcomes. the legal system constantly misgenders trans women, putting them in men’s jails no matter how well she passes as a woman, which puts these women as incredible risks for their safety and lives. 
misgendering is a social and sometimes fatal power that cis people have over trans people, and acting as if it’s at all times “a honest mistake” shows how little you think of trans peoples’ security.

text:
Shout out to people who didn’t go to any pride celebrations this month for any reason:

-No proper transportation/ it was too far away

-Work or social responsibilities prevented you

-You’re not out for any number of reasons

-It was discouraged by family

-A chronic illness or disability prevented you

-Generally inaccessibility of celebrations

-You wouldn’t feel comfortable due to part of your identity (could be race or where you fit into the LGBTQ umbrella or other)

-You wouldn’t feel safe for the above reasons or any other

-You didn’t want to/couldn’t for any other reason

-Hell, you were just too lazy

You’re no less valid! Going to a pride celebration is not a requirement of being LGBTQ. Let’s continue spreading the love and acceptance I keep seeing on Tumblr no matter the month!

text:
Sometimes it’s difficult for people to seek contact with each other because they can feel intimidated by others. Using this meme, you can send the symbols to my askbox that represent to you how intimidating I am to you. This way, it could be more clear to both sides how things are based on these feelings.
😗 - YOU ARE THE SOFTEST BEING.
😀 - I’m not afraid of reaching out to you.
😃 - To me, you are easy to approach.
😊 - I think you are a really friendly person.
😶 - I’m not sure if I can reach out to you.
😐 - You seem a little distant from others.
😓 - I feel like you would not really like me.
😲 - I’m afraid of reaching out to you.
😟 - I wish I had the courage to start talking to you.
😥 - I am very intimidated by you. I wish it wasn’t that way, because you seem cool.
😫 - I admire you from the sidelines because you seem cool and I’m just a dork.
😧 - Senpai, notice me????
😦 - I feel really insecure when I want to reach out to you.
😨 - You intimidate me….a whole damn lot.
😭 - I wish I could be your friend but to me, you are so hard to reach out to.
😱 - I am so incredibly intimidated by you, it even makes me a little anxious sometimes.
💀 - OH MY GOD DON’T EAT ME PLEASE

text:
“Lesbian” is a term used for a woman attracted to another woman. That being a cis woman, a trans woman, or a nonbinary female-aligned person. 
“He/him” are pronouns directly linked to males. He/him pronouns are used for people who identify, in some way, as male. Cis men, trans men, and nonbinary male-aligned people most likely use he/him pronouns.
Pronouns are still important in relation to gender. You can’t identify as female but go by he/him pronouns. You also can’t identify as male but go by she/her pronouns. It doesn’t work that way. 
Identifying as a lesbian but going by he/him pronouns is transphobic, even if you aren’t intending to be transphobic. Claiming you’re a ‘he/him lesbian’ but using he/him pronouns enforces the narrative that trans men are still ‘female’, since lesbians are female and he/him pronouns are male.
In conclusion: he/him lesbianism is a huge juxtaposition and is not an identity.
However, there are other potential identities you could go by.
You could, in fact, be a straight trans man. That means you are a trans man attracted to women, cis or trans. This does not mean you aren’t part of the LGBT community. It’s okay to be a straight trans man. You’re valid.
Alternatively, if you do identify as female, you can be a butch lesbian. I’m not too educated enough on the topic of the femme-butch lesbian scale, but I strongly advise looking into it.
Finally, it’s also possible you could be bigender or genderfluid, or maybe even demi-girl. If that is the case, you should take the time to look into these identities, too.
I hope this helps shed some light on the situation.

text:
I hope no physical harm comes to you, but I also hope that one day you will see the harm in the dogma you spread.
I hope that you one day see that trans women are still women. If you equate having a vagina to being a woman, you are holding yourself back. You are taking away all of what it means to be a woman. All of the strength and power. You are reducing womanhood to a single physical characteristic.
I hope that one day you see that being born with a vagina also doesn’t automatically make you a woman. I hope you can come to see the struggles of trans men and non binary people with vaginas.
We as trans people do not simply transition because “being a woman is hard” or because we’re brainwashed by society or any external force. This is internal. This is the reality of what we are on the inside. It’s not a copout because “being gay is too difficult so I’m gonna just change my gender”.
Trans people are sexually harassed. We are denied opportunities for who we are. Instead of seeing the similarities in our struggles, you push us away and call us liars.
I hope self reflection finds you well.
Sincerely,
A non-binary person
(With a vagina, since I know some of you won’t listen unless I put that private information out there)., PREACH

text:
I am a dude with a boyfriend.
We’re both Asian.
We went on a bus and sat in front of two girls.
I kissed behind his ear (and then he punched me in the arm, he’s shy in public) and I heard one of them whisper to the other something along the lines of “We get to see close up yaoi on here!”.
(Neither of us are even Japanese)
I was kinda offended, so I took my boyfriend by the hand and left.
It made us feel very uncomfortable.
I just want to say:
Our love and relationship isn’t for your entertainment.
Nor is it here for you to fetishize and sexualize.
Please just keep your “yaoi xDD” to just fiction, and please do not call us “yaoi”.
Many dismiss this as not a problem, which I find rude as they have never experienced this so they don’t really have much to say against this.
Thank you for reading.
